            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "For Svetlana Petrova, life\u2019s most pivotal moments are measured in flavors and aromas. Born in Leningrad in the final decades of the Soviet Union, her childhood was defined by the comforting scent of her *babushka\u2019s* kitchen\u2014the earthy sweetness of simmering borscht and the savory steam of handmade *pelmeni*. This culinary heritage was a pocket of warmth and abundance in a world of scarcity, planting a seed that would later flourish across the world.\n\nThe fall of the Iron Curtain brought chaotic promise. In the mid-1990s, Svetlana and her family immigrated to the United States, drawn to the established Russian community nestled within the fog-laced avenues of San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District. The early years were a struggle of language barriers and dishwashing jobs in bustling, anonymous kitchens. Yet, within that clatter, she found her calling. Determined to master the business, she enrolled at San Francisco State University, earning a Bachelor\u2019s in Hospitality Management while working her way up from line cook to sous chef.\n\nThe turning point came ten years ago. At 40, Svetlana pooled her life savings and secured a small business loan to open \"Dacha,\" her own restaurant in the Inner Richmond. It was a terrifying leap of faith, a tribute to the grandmother who taught her that food was love. She became not just the owner, but the heart of the kitchen, her hands shaping the same dough she\u2019d learned to make as a girl.\n\nToday, at 50, Svetlana\u2019s life is her restaurant. Her day begins before dawn, sourcing produce at the Alemany Farmers' Market, and ends late, after the last customer has left satisfied. Her 2.5-mile drive home to her modest Outer Richmond condo is often her only quiet time. Her social circle is a tight-knit tapestry of loyal staff, longtime patrons, and a few fellow Russian-American friends with whom she shares stories of the old world and the new. Her daughter, now at UCLA, represents a more assimilated generation, but still helps wait tables during breaks.\n\nSvetlana\u2019s dream is no longer about growth, but legacy. She hopes Dacha will remain a beloved neighborhood institution, a sanctuary of authenticity. She aspires to one day write a cookbook, preserving her family's recipes, and perhaps take a long-overdue trip to St. Petersburg\u2014not as a tourist, but to walk the streets of her past with the quiet confidence of a woman who built her own American dream from a foundation of flour, memory, and resilience."
